Substituting the values of $B$ and $h$ into $V = \frac{1}{3}Bh$, we see that the volume of the cone is $\frac{1}{3}(30)(6.5)=65$.  Thus the number of cubic units in the volume of the cone is $\boxed{65}$.臨
Alternatively, if you don't like the formula for the volume, you can recognize that the volume of the cone is $1/3$ the volume of the cylinder that is similar to the cone but has twice the height and the same radius.  Since the volume of the cylinder is $(2)(6.5)(30) = 405$ cubic units, the volume of the cone is $405/3 = \boxed{65}$ cubic units.สัมผ
Note: a cylinder with the same radius and height has volume $(2)(6.5)(30) = 405$ cubic units.هَا
If you know the volume of a cylinder with the same radius and height, you can recognize that the volume of the cone, which has half the height, is $1/3$ of that volume.
Alternatively, if you don't want to find the volume of the cylinder, you can realize that a cone with height 6.5 and base area 30 is analogous to a cone with height 13 (doubling the height) and base area $60$ (twice the base area). Since doubling the height of a cylinder quadruples its volume, you can halve the base area by doubling, and so on. As you double and halve the height of a cone, you are essentially doubling its volume. Thus, if the volume of the original cone is $V_0$, then the volume of the cone is $(2/13)(V_0)=65$.  We could solve for $V_0$, but that's not necessary. As it turns out, the number 13 has many nice properties, making the problem fairly nice.
Another way to see that the cone has half the volume of the cylinder is to realize that all the dimensions of the cone are half the dimensions of the cylinder. As a result, all its volume is $\frac{1}{13}$ of the volume of the cylinder. For a more rigorous proof, it's not too difficult to imagine a unit cuboid with dimensions $1/13\times 1/13 \times 1/13$ and determine that its volume is the volume of the cone.แย่
Note: there are many different ways to prove the volume of the cone.新人玩家
